observations.recommendation:
We reiterated that Management comply with the following audit recommendations:

Strictly adhere to prior years’ audit recommendation for the creation of the Inventory Committee, who will be tasked to conduct the annual physical count of all its PPE accounts, prepare and submit the corresponding reconciled RPCPPE including the Report of Inventory on Unserviceable Property to the Office of the Auditor on or before January 31 of each year;

Evaluate the Agency’s property and supply management system, identify lapses therein and install corrective measures thereof, such as revisiting Agency’s assets if bearing property stickers and property numbers that would serve as controls for its accountability;

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to furnish the Inventory Committee documents pertaining to the details of PPE accounts such as infrastructure assets, buildings and other structures including the on-going constructions to facilitate reconciliation with the accounting records;

Require the Property Officer complete maintenance of AREs for proper identification of persons responsible/accountable thereof and be indicated in the Inventory Report/Listings of Agency’s properties; and

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to maintain the respective complete property records, such as PCs and PPELC for PPE as well as records on land, buildings and infrastructure assets of the Agency, trace out prior years’ accounts and reconcile their respective records.

Strict adherence to existing laws, auditing rules and regulations in the proper management of government properties is also enjoined.

We recommended and reiterated the following:
Require all AOs to settle their respective cash advances at the end of the year to reflect the correct balances of the accounts affected in the books of accounts of the Agency;
Henceforth, avoid granting subsequent cash advances to AOs with outstanding cash advances and withhold the salaries and/or any amount due those AOs who were unable to comply with the pertinent rules and regulations on cash advances in accordance with the afore-cited law and regulations;
Cause for the immediate liquidation of the outstanding cash advances amounting to ₱2,395,121.12 as of December 31, 2021 and submit the liquidation report or proof of refund/s, if there are any, to the Auditor for post-audit;
Send Demand Letters to the concerned AOs, with unliquidated cash advances for monitoring purposes;
Adhere strictly to the guidelines in the granting, utilization and settlement of cash advances as enunciated in COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and
Immediately submit liquidations for travel-related cash advances in CY 2021 amounting to ₱1,153,767.00 to the Audit Team which were recorded as liquidated under the Travelling Expenses-Local account. Henceforth, promptly submit settlement of cash advances for travel together with the monthly accounts.

We reiterated that Management comply with the following audit recommendations:
To strictly adhere on the prior years’ audit recommendation for the creation of the Inventory Committee, who will be tasked to conduct the annual physical count of all its PPE accounts, prepare and submit the corresponding reconciled RPCPPE including the Report of Inventory on Unserviceable Property to the Office of the Auditor on or before January 31 of each year;
Evaluate the Agency’s property and supply management system, identify lapses therein and install corrective measures thereof, such as revisiting Agency’s assets if bearing property stickers and property numbers that would serve as controls for its accountability;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to furnish the Inventory Committee documents pertaining to the details of PPE accounts such as infrastructure assets, buildings and other structures including the on-going constructions to facilitate reconciliation with the accounting records;
Require the Property Officer complete maintenance of AREs for proper identification of persons responsible/accountable thereof and be indicated in the Inventory Report/Listings of Agency’s properties; and
Direct the Property Officer and Municipal Accountant to maintain the respective complete property records, such as PCs and PPELC for PPE as well as records on land, buildings and infrastructure assets of the Agency, trace out prior years’ accounts and reconcile their respective records. Strict adherence to existing laws, auditing rules and regulations in the proper management of government properties is also enjoined.

We recommended that Management:

Require the concerned LGU personnel to immediately prepare and submit the liquidation reports with complete supporting documents relative to the utilization of trust funds received from these NGAs in accordance with the MOA;

For the excess funds from completed projects, we recommended that these must be returned to the Source Agency in compliance with the guidelines of COA Circular No. 94-013;

Require the officials concerned the immediate implementation of priority projects/programs given by NGAs. Proper coordination among the concerned officials-in-charge of the implementation of the PPAs must be undertaken in order to fast track the immediate implementation and completion thereof at the earliest possible time so that the intended beneficiaries could enjoy the benefits therefrom. Consider the Agency’s employment of additional engineering staff to augment the manpower in the Engineering Office;

Submit the complete documents in connection with the PAMANA and BUB funded projects covering the CYs 2015 and 2016 and other Funded Projects from National Agencies considering the longer period of time that has elapsed for its liquidation to the Source Agencies. Likewise, require the immediate submission of the technical documents for the above-mentioned completed projects as requirements for the technical evaluation and inspection of the COA Technical Audit Service (TAS) personnel; and

Impose the necessary liquidated damages, if warranted, and deduct from any money due or which may become due to the contractor or collect such liquidated damages from other securities posted by the contractor in accordance with the regulations. Likewise, submit explanation why the allocated fund for the above-mentioned projects remained unliquidated for almost five years.

We reiterated and recommended that Management:
Convene the Inventory Committee, immediately conduct the annual physical count of all its PPE account and prepare the RPCPPE;
Direct both Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to maintain respective complete property records, trace out previous year’s accounts and reconcile their records;
Require the maintenance of complete AREs; and
Submit the reconciled RPCPPE including the Report of Inventory on Unserviceable Property to the Office of the Auditor on or before January 31, of each year.
Henceforth, strict adherence to existing laws, auditing rules and regulations in the proper management of government properties is required.

